  <billdetail>
    <title>Ngati Tuwharetoa, Raukawa, and Te Arawa River Iwi Waikato River Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Māori Affairs Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM3191500" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="143" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2010">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Māori Affairs Committee has examined the Ngati Tuwharetoa, Raukawa, and Te Arawa River Iwi Waikato River Bill, and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Ngati Tuwharetoa, Raukawa, and Te Arawa River Iwi Waikato River Bill would give effect to deeds entered into between the Crown and Ngāti Tūwharetoa, Raukawa, and Te Arawa River Iwi, by which the Crown and each iwi would agree to a co-governance framework for the Waikato River and its catchment and co-management and related arrangements in order to restore and protect the health and wellbeing of the Waikato River for present and future generations.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>This bill complements arrangements agreed between the Crown and Waikato-Tainui in a deed of settlement signed on 17 December 2009, parts of which are legislated for (in respect of Waikato-Tainui) in the Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Act 2010. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Joint management agreements</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending clauses 46(3), 47(4), and 48(4) to make it clear that each party would bear their own costs of complying with the joint management agreements. This would make the clauses consistent with the provisions in the Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Act and would also take away any uncertainty over responsibility for costs.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also recommend amending clauses 49(1) and 49(2) by removing the 10-day requirement to convene a joint working party within 10 working days of the operative date or written notice from the Tūwharetoa Māori Trust Board, and replacing it with a requirement to convene within 30 working days. Allowing only 10 business days to convene a joint working party is impractical, and a 30-day timeframe is viable and consistent with the Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Act.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Te Arawa Lakes</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We heard from Te Arawa Lakes Trust that the three Te Arawa lakes in the catchment of the Upper Waikato River, which have been vested in the trust since a 2006 settlement, would not be covered by the co-management arrangements in the bill, and that this may prevent the trust from entering into arrangements with local authorities, in particular, Environment Waikato. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>The relevant beneficiaries of the trust are all of Te Arawa and are therefore represented in the co-management arrangements by Te Arawa River Iwi Trust. While we note the concerns of the Te Arawa Lakes Trust, we consider that they and the Te Arawa River Iwi Trust should work together on the joint management agreements to reflect Te Arawa interests and ensure that the lakes are provided for. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We recommend no amendment.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Upper Waipā River</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We considered but did not support a request from Maniopoto Māori Trust Board to amend the bill to include a description of the limit of Raukawa’s interests in the catchment of the Upper Waipā River and to provide for Maniopoto to participate in the joint management agreements between Raukawa and local authorities within that catchment. We strongly believe that overlapping interests should be resolved by iwi themselves, and that it is not the Crown’s place to legislate iwi interests. Maniopoto is currently negotiating its own deed with the Crown. We are confident that these negotiations and continued talks between Raukawa and Maniopoto will address the concerns of the iwi involved. We consider that the iwi will be able to deal with any issues of overlapping interests within the co-management arrangements provided for in the bill.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Waikato River Authority membership</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We heard submissions that the membership of the Waikato River Authority should be increased from 10 to 12 to give Ngāti Korokī Kahukura representation. It was proposed that an additional Crown member could be nominated by the Federated Farmers of New Zealand. As we did when considering the Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Act, we gave serious thought to Ngāti Korokī Kahukura’s need for recognition as a river iwi and to be heard in respect of their Tupuna Awa. We believe that a way should be found for them to achieve their aspirations.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We remain convinced that to be most effective, the maximum size of the Waikato River Authority should remain at 10. We note that the membership can be re-examined during the review process for the authority at a later date. In the meantime, we understand that the iwi is currently negotiating with the Crown for the settlement of its non-raupatu historical Treaty claims, and we encourage both parties to use this process to address the iwi’s concerns.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend no amendment.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Regulations and bylaws</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend inserting new clause 57(A) into the bill to give effect to a clause in the Ngāti Tūwharetoa deed that would protect the iwi’s pre-existing arrangements. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We heard from commercial fisheries representatives who were concerned about the effect that the bill would have on their fishing rights. We were advised that the bill is consistent with the Fisheries Act 1996 and with the equivalent provisions in the Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Act, and confers no powers to levy or impose charges on fishers. We were also advised that, in practice, the “undue adverse effects” test applied by the Ministry of Fisheries to determine whether to permit bylaws to restrict or prohibit fishing is already separately applied to commercial, customary, and recreational classes of fishing, so commercial fishing would not be disproportionately affected.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We are satisfied that fisheries stakeholders will continue to be consulted whenever regulations are made. The bill would require them to be made under the Fisheries Act, which already provides for proper consultation with affected parties. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Relationship to Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Act </heading>
        <para>
          <text>The co-governance framework and co-management arrangements for the Waikato River were initiated by negotiations between the Crown and Waikato-Tainui during the settlement of Treaty claims in respect of the Waikato River. Ngāti Tūwharetoa, Raukawa, and Te Arawa River Iwi subsequently negotiated their own arrangements directly with the Crown. Significant parts of this bill replicate parts of the Waikato-Tainui Raupatu Claims (Waikato River) Settlement Act, and we consider that it may be appropriate for the bill to include an acknowledgement of the relationship between the two pieces of legislation. This would promote clarity and consistency, and thus their effective implementation. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>While we do not recommend an amendment at this time, we encourage the Crown to discuss this possibility with all the iwi involved and to consider amending the legislation in the future.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Ngati Tuwharetoa, Raukawa, and Te Arawa River Iwi Waikato River Bill was referred to the committee on 28 July 2010. The closing date for submissions was 6 August 2010. We received and considered 18 submissions from interested groups including iwi organisations, local authorities, and fisheries and farming stakeholders. We heard 14 submissions at a hearing in Rotorua.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Office of Treaty Settlements.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
